n of successive executive efforts to grapple with gross social and economic disparities in the United States. Huret argues that this internal war, coming at a time of great disruption due to the Cold War, undermined and fractured the institutional system officially directed at ending poverty. The official War on Poverty, which arguably reached its peak under President Lyndon B. Johnson, was thus fomented and maintained by a group of experts determined to fight poverty in radical ways that outstripped both the operational capacity of the federal government and the political will of a succession of presidents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoorzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPovertyxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPovertyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aPublic Policy. 4aU.S. History.  apoverty in postwar america, Welfare state, war on poverty, Lyndon B. Johnson, poverty.1 aAngell, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501709531?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501709531/original  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Histo